description: {"blocks":[{"key":"1q86q","text":"This protocols is part of the ANU Biosecurity mini-research project #1 \"Plant Pathogen Diagnostics: Visuals, subcultures, and genomics\". ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3ujbg","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"rchm","text":"You will be provided four pots of 3-4 week old wheat plants that have been infected with different wheat pathogens. Each pot has been infected with one major pathogen. You will not know which pot has been infected with which pathogen. However, you will be provided a compendium of 10-15 wheat pathogens that will guide you to identify the infective agent for each treatment group. The fifth treatment group will be uninfected wheat plants which will be clearly identified. You can use treatment group #5 as negative control for your experiments.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fpanu","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a8md5","text":"In total, each group will obtain five pots each:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2mq9p","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1b7cs","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"1o259","text":"This specific protocol is a step by step guide to perform PCR reactions on the extracted DNA samples of the five TG. The two PCR reaction target conserved marker regions (a.k.a. metabarcodes) for two kingdoms. With 16S primers targeting bacteria and ITS primers targeting fungi. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f8vqr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6pb3v","text":"The simplified idea of metabarcodes is that one can amplify a region that is conserved enough to generate primers that allow one to amplify this region from \"all\" members of the kindgom somewhat representatively. Within the amplicon though there are located hypervariable regions that are distinct between different species or genera. Matching these amplicons against a databases let's one identify the organism of this specific kingdom present in the sample. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3ssk9","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5b4nf","text":"At least this is the simple theory, however as you will see in the lectures there are many issues and biases to consider when applying these techniques in general and specifically to pathogen diagnostics for biosecurity purposes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9quuk","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5a1is","text":"The final goal is to achieve the following:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"for8u","text":"To measure and adjust DNA concentration for each sample to allow for equal amount of DNA being added to each sample.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6c86a","text":"Perform PCR reaction for the fungal kingdom metabarcode using published ITS (Internal transcribed spacer) primers.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5g1hv","text":"Perform PCR reaction for the bacterial kingdom metabarcode using published 16S primers.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"565mt","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d2o7e","text":"This protocol is applicable for week 4. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3bf4r","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6n9ea","text":"Protocols progress overview:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4t7e8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"47riq","text":"Week 4 PCR reaction for 16S and ITS.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2norg","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bq4lj","text":"You will measure double stranded DNA concentration with a dye based method. Here the dye binds to double stranded DNA only and this will change the fluorescent of the dye in a way directly proportional to the DNA concentration. You will use the pre-mixed broad range dye kit https://www.thermofisher.com/order/catalog/product/Q32853.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":275,"length":57}],"data":{}},{"key":"46s7c","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ev26c","text":"The primers for the ITS PCR reactions are called ITSFor and ITSRev. These are based on White et. al., 1989 and have the following sequences.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bgtup","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9elja","text":"ITSFor (a.k.a. NS5): 5'-AACTTAAAGGAATTGACGGAAG-3'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a807s","text":"ITSRev (a.k.a.LR6): 5'-CGCCAGTTCTGCTTACC-3'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7la9j","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"21jq1","text":"The expected amplicon size is around 2.5 to 3 kb (kilobase pairs).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4a3bs","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"75rav","text":"The primers for the 16S PCR reaction are called 16SFor and 16SRev. These are based on Wuyts et. al., 2002, Baker et. al., 2003, and Youssef et. al., 2009.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"75ta0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"67u9e","text":"16SFor (a.k.a. 27F, E8F, or E8Fa): 5'-AGAGTTTGATCCTGGCTCAG-3'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e2vj4","text":"16SRev (a.k.a. 1492R): 5'-ACCTTGTTACGACTT-3'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"qcg1","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c7svk","text":"Importantly, these 16S primers also partially bind and amplify 16S regions found in plant mitochondria and chloroplast. The amplification of the plant 16S region has to be therefore inhibited with sequence specific probes called PNAs (Peptide mediated Nucleic Acids) https://www.pnabio.com/products/PCR_blocker.htm. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":2,"offset":267,"length":47}],"data":{}},{"key":"16qsd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"63ca4","text":"We will use the following PNAs for the 16S PCR reactions. These are based on Lundberg et a. 2013.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"55o9n","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"58m6g","text":"The anti-mitochondrial PNA (mPNA): 5′-GGCAAGTGTTCTTCGGA-3′","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"991q5","text":"The anti-plastid PNA (pPNA): 5′-GGCTCAACCCTGGACAG-3′","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1ugh6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ci7v1","text":"References:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cdktf","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a5h3a","text":"White, Bruns, Lee and Taylor, 1989, 'Amplification and direct sequencing of fungal ribosomal RNA Genes for phylogenetics', in PCR - Protocols and Applications - A Laboratory Manual, Academic Press ","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e5qie","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"27p1m","text":"Wuyts, Van de Peer, Winkelmans and De Wachter, 2002, 'The European database on small subunit ribosomal RNA', Nuc. steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"c23vj","text":"The first section describes the quantification of extracted DNA from week 3. Once you know the concentration for each TG you can generate a DNA stock solution at a final concentration of 10 ng/ul. This stock solution for each TG will be used for the following PCR reaction and DNA quality control measures in week 5.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6jg3c","text":"You will receive your DNA extracts from the previous practical session in week 3. You should receive five tubes in total containing the DNA for each TG.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"fv93m","text":"Measure DNA concentration with Qubit broad range (BR).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6l9pg","text":"You will receive five tubes containing 198uL BR Qubit reaction ready to use. Label the tubes with treatment group name.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6faib","text":"For each TG, add 2uL of DNA extracted to the corresponding BR Qubit tube. Make sure to add the correct DNA sample to the correctly labelled BR tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"80grq","text":"Vortex your BR Qubit tube containing the DNA.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"eamj8","text":"Collect the liquid at the bottom of the tube with a quick \"hand-centrifuge\".","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"1je6t","text":"Incubate for 1-5 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"9jihh","text":"Wipe down the outside of your tube with a Kim wipe.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"b3ud5","text":"Measure your concentration using the Qubit machine. Demonstrators will facilitate the measurement. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"admsn","text":"Note down the concentration of each TG DNA sample in ng/ul.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8fp61","text":"Now for each TG, dilute the DNA sample to a concentration of 10 ng/ul with nuclease free water. Make up a DNA total stock solution of 100ul. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9fdee","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"aqlq9","text":"The important formula here is: ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"mrt0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5j5gq","text":"n = c*V with n being the amount in ng, c the concentration in ng/ul, and V the volume.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"42i8r","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fk7h3","text":"You want V = 100ul and c =10 ng/ul. This means you will have 1000ng in 100 ul.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fq3k5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7kfom","text":"The question is how much volume of the original DNA do you need to obtain 1000ngs?","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f9mqk","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bmmrp","text":"Here now n = 1000ng and c equals your measured concentration. Let's assume your measured c = 56 ng/ul for an assumed sample. Than we can resolve the equation as follows.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6ga4o","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7rs36","text":"n = c*V -\u003e V = n/c -\u003e 1000ng/56ng/ul =  17.85 ul","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"64c57","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cql0e","text":"So you need to use 17.85ul in 100ul total volume to obtain 1000ng. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5n7fc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"m00b","text":"This means you need to mix 17.85ul of extracted DNA (c = 56 ng/ul) and mix it with 82.15 ul nuclease free water to obtain your final 100ul @ 10 ng/ul DNA stock solution.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c62np","text":"For each TG, calculate the required volume of extracted DNA and nuclease free water to obtain your final 100ul @ 10 ng/ul DNA stock solution. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dhnap","text":"Label five 1.5ml tubes with your research group name, treatment group name, date, and the DNA concentration 100 ng/ul.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"2b2d0","text":"Check with a demonstrator that your calculations are correct","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"gnsv","text":"For each TG, mix the the required volume of extracted DNA and nuclease free water to obtain your final 100ul @ 10 ng/ul DNA stock solution. Mix the sample by pipetting up and down.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9iiap","text":"You now should have five DNA stock solution tubes, one for each TG. These are the DNA solutions you will need for the PCR reactions below and the DNA quality control measures in week 5. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1qkt1","text":"Now you will amplify the ITS regions in the DNA samples you extracted from wheat leaves. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9bken","text":"You will use the DNA stock solutions and 50 ng per reaction. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7ofm7","text":"You will use a proof-reading polymerase to reduce the errors introduced during PCR. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f5316","text":"You will use the following primer set for amplification.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c6i27","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eaf1u","text":"ITSFor: 5'-AACTTAAAGGAATTGACGGAAG-3'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4som9","text":"ITSRev: 5'-CGCCAGTTCTGCTTACC-3'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"65kal","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
